    <text xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">
        <body>
            <head>22. Memorandum From the Executive Secretary of the <orgName
                    corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department of State</orgName> (<persName
                    corresp="recbqCAmrwoV1cgSm">Bremer</persName>) to the President’s Assistant for
                National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI"
                    >Clark</persName>)<note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d22fn1">Source:
                        <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName> Library, <persName
                        corresp="reccYhPleLdoqXAck">Matlock</persName> Files, Head of State
                    Correspondence (US—<gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>) Jan.—May 1982.
                    Secret; Sensitive. Drafted by <persName corresp="recH68EY4ISVFpkiS"
                        >Vershbow</persName>; cleared by <persName corresp="recBbyyU6ZEkgteau"
                        >Simons</persName>, <persName corresp="recC5ROimAtQ4UkBp"
                    >Scanlan</persName>, <persName corresp="reccOrOPn6TsvnrGI">Burt</persName>, and
                        <persName corresp="recLQOseWL1SmhqS7">Stoessel</persName>.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1982-05-21"
                        >May 21, 1982</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>
                    <persName corresp="recH9FNqGx0jGXjsD">Brezhnev</persName>’s Reply to <persName
                        corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName>’s May 7 Letter</item>
            </list>
            <p>Soviet Chargé <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Aleksandr Bessmertnykh</persName>
                today gave <persName corresp="recLQOseWL1SmhqS7">Walt Stoessel</persName>
                <persName corresp="recH9FNqGx0jGXjsD">Brezhnev</persName>’s reply to <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName>’s May 7 letter.<note n="2"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d22fn2">See <ref target="#d16">Document 16</ref>.</note>
                The May 20 letter<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d22fn3">See <ref
                        target="frus1981-88v03#d171">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. III,
                        Soviet Union, January 1981–January 1983, Document 171</ref>.</note> neither
                accepts nor rejects our proposed late-June date for beginning <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs>
                </gloss>. After self-righteously chastizing us for a year and a half of
                footdragging, however, <persName corresp="recH9FNqGx0jGXjsD">Brezhnev</persName>
                does agree that diplomatic discussions should begin “in the near future” on the
                questions of time and venue for the talks. The Soviets probably do not want to
                appear to have jumped at our proposed date, but we expect they will ultimately agree
                to begin talks in the June-July period. Moscow may want to drag things out to permit
                a formal announcement when and if <persName corresp="recDnAZMmGID4lGnZ"
                    >Gromyko</persName> and Secretary <persName corresp="receeGTv8IaT6tukJ"
                    >Haig</persName> meet in New York during the <gloss target="#t_SSOD_1"
                    >SSOD</gloss> (probably the week of June 21).<note n="4" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d22fn4">
                    <persName corresp="receeGTv8IaT6tukJ">Haig</persName> met with <persName
                        corresp="recDnAZMmGID4lGnZ">Gromyko</persName> in New York on June 18. A
                    record of their conversation is printed in <ref target="frus1981-88v03#d186">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. III,
                        Soviet Union, January 1981–January 1983, Document 186</ref>. Prior to the
                    meeting, <persName corresp="receeGTv8IaT6tukJ">Haig</persName> informed
                        <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName> that, regarding <rs
                        corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms control</rs>, he would “put
                        <persName corresp="recDnAZMmGID4lGnZ">Gromyko</persName> on the defensive”
                    by building on <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName>’s UNSSOD
                    speech. “The message will be that we have a sensible and comprehensive program
                    for negotiating improved security for both sides through significant reduction,”
                        <persName corresp="receeGTv8IaT6tukJ">Haig</persName> added, and that “the
                    Soviets cannot be serious when they accuse us of not being sincere; and that it
                    is up to them to demonstrate in negotiations that they really favor <rs
                        corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms control</rs>.” (<ref
                        target="frus1981-88v03#d185">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. III,
                        Soviet Union, January 1981–January 1983, Document 185</ref>)</note>
                <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName> told <persName
                    corresp="recLQOseWL1SmhqS7">Walt Stoessel</persName> that he hoped to <pb
                    facs="0115" n="86" xml:id="pg_86"/> have further instructions on Monday<note
                    n="5" place="foot" xml:id="d22fn5">May 24.</note> concerning a <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs>
                </gloss> starting date.</p>
            <p>The bulk of <persName corresp="recH9FNqGx0jGXjsD">Brezhnev</persName>’s letter is
                devoted to an attack on our <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs>
                </gloss> proposal as presented in the <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                    >President</persName>’s <orgName corresp="recehQeTv0JdEphg1">Eureka</orgName>
                    speech,<note n="6" place="foot" xml:id="d22fn6">See <ref target="#d17">Document
                        17</ref>.</note> followed by a pitch in support of <persName
                    corresp="recH9FNqGx0jGXjsD">Brezhnev</persName>’s May 18 proposal<note n="7"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d22fn7">Reference is to <persName
                        corresp="recH9FNqGx0jGXjsD">Brezhnev</persName>’s May 18 speech to the
                    Komsomol, in <hi rendition="simple_italic">Current Digest of the Soviet
                        Press</hi>, vol. 34, no. 20, June 16, 1982, pp. 1–23. In a May 19 memorandum
                    to <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="receeGTv8IaT6tukJ">Haig</persName> described the speech as “clearly
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">aimed at public opinion</hi> in the <placeName
                        corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName> and especially
                        <placeName corresp="recbVRIDL9rshpLzN">Western Europe</placeName>. It
                    emphasizes grand gestures, both in <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs>
                    </gloss> and <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                        <rs corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9" type="event">INF</rs>
                    </gloss>, but gives little insight into the Soviet negotiating approach.” (See
                        <ref target="frus1981-88v03#d173">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. III,
                        Soviet Union, January 1981–January 1983, Document 173</ref>)</note> for a
                US-Soviet <rs corresp="recAynYh8uzxYGQRH" type="topic">strategic weapons</rs>
                freeze. <persName corresp="recH9FNqGx0jGXjsD">Brezhnev</persName> declares flatly
                that our proposal “is not a realistic position, not the path toward agreement.” He
                claims that our approach, by singling out one aspect of the strategic equation
                (land-based missiles), would mean substantial reductions only for the Soviet side.
                He fails to acknowledge <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the
                    President</persName>’s subsequent assertions that “everything is negotiable,”
                including <rs corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE" type="topic">bombers</rs> and <rs
                    corresp="recqaxqBsfTYVWHfR" type="topic">cruise missiles</rs>, and the fact that
                the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> would have to make
                substantial cuts in sea-based missiles.</p>
            <p>On the question of a freeze, <persName corresp="recH9FNqGx0jGXjsD"
                    >Brezhnev</persName> makes the predictable argument that such an agreement would
                create “favorable conditions” for <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs>
                </gloss> negotiations, and calls on <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the
                    President</persName> to give his proposal careful consideration. He makes clear
                that the proposal would limit <rs corresp="recbm2CDfl6YlSCnq">modernization</rs> and
                not just freeze the number of strategic systems, which makes it all the more
                one-sided in the Soviets’ favor.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recbqCAmrwoV1cgSm">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">L. Paul Bremer, III</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">Executive Secretary</hi>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
